text: January 2023 We were on holiday in Vietnam when my husband became seriously ill. The resort we were staying at A Lam organised for him to go to this hospital. He was quickly assessed with blood test and X-ray and diagnosed as having pneumonia. In a hospital bed within an hour. The doctor, Lai Quoc Thai, who is the head of the unit was exceptional. Highly competent and spoke excellent English. His team of nurses were really helpful too. What you need to know is a stay in hospital requires a carer to support the sick person so I stayed on a bed next to hubby. Reason being is the hospital doesn‚Äôt provide food or drinks. Opposite the hospital is a group of food providers which also give one somewhere to go. The hospital is very close to a very large shopping centre with a supermarket inside it. We are so grateful to the doctor and staff. We spent 5 nights there and flew back to Sydney with good information for our local doctor. Highly recommend this hospital. We also took a room at Spring hotel near hospital to do washing and for me to shower in only $27 a night and reasonable good. There are showers there but wanted a bit more privacy. This is a horrible place. If you turn up, you wait hours to see a doctor. They tell you to call first, which is reasonable, but when you call and ask for English, they repeatedly just hang up on you. This is the worst hospital service in Binh Duong.

Excellent hospital for delivery BUT head elsewhere for child vaccinations. Clean facilities, large rooms, and friendly staff, at least when they're dealing with pregnant women. My wife's single-bed postnatal room was worth every penny. The room (~30m2 or 320ft2) had a spacious bathroom, TV, closet, sofa, desk, large bed, and an AC. However, you should head over to VNVC for your child's vaccinations. The hospital regularly ran out of vaccines. We called the customer service line several times to inquire about the next shipment of vaccines or alternative locations but the girl on the line just snapped saying she doesn't know and hung up abruptly. Definitely the daughter of a cadre or a upper-level management who isn't afraid of getting fired...
5 stars for the facility but 1 star for the superiorly bad service. Employees are trained to treat patients like trash.

text: The hospital is very clean and professional but still needs improvement. It must be said that the hospital is clean and professional from every step because it corresponds to the amount of money the patient spends. There is quite a lot of green space in the hospital, making patients feel somewhat comfortable. Prices are of course higher than public hospitals. Health insurance is applied but pays very little, most patients pay themselves. The lowest price for a room to stay if accompanied by a caregiver is about 450k (after deducting health insurance). The staff also gives quite thoughtful instructions. I had an ENT check-up and my teeth were still quite OK. The doctor listens and explains to the patient. Anyone who wants a quick examination can make an appointment through the hotline to have an examination schedule and arrange flexible hours. If examined in the afternoon, it is more comfortable, less sick and does not need to be booked in advance. The canteen is also quite full of food and drinks, spacious and airy. Prices are a bit higher than outside. Some suggestions: - It's quite inconvenient to have to wait a day to issue an invoice, and workers have to waste time going back to the hospital to get it when the road is reversed. - The emergency department security guard is a bit distracted and a bit sloppy (not trained according to international standards). - The parking lot is too far from the emergency department, so it is quite inconvenient, so a small space should be allowed to park motorbikes to provide first aid to patients.

My wife was hospitalized at Becamex Hospital, from the time of admission to the time of discharge was 42 hours, but the hospital calculated the number of days of hospitalization as 3 days. I find this unreasonable, because I used the service for less than 2 days (ie less than 48 hours) but paid for 3 days. I asked her to leave the hospital, but it was difficult to make it easier, no communication. Obviously, the procedures are cumbersome. To put it bluntly, the goal is to make the patient stay as long as possible, because the room fee for just one day is nearly 500K. If customers do not need to stay for medical examination and treatment but are forced to stay, the relationship between the Hospital and the Patient will actually soon end because of the lack of ATTITUDE FOR THE PATIENT. I will NEVER GO BACK TO USE THE SERVICES HERE AGAIN. Everyone should read the comments carefully before coming to this hospital!

The second time I return to the hospital as a caregiver, I have a few comments: - Security is very good, full information is checked, the security guards are very welcoming when assisting. - Hygiene in the hospital is very good, but sometimes there is still a fishy smell in the ward hallway. If it could be improved, it would be great. - Regarding food, there is no food at the ward for patients like some other hospitals. It's a bit inconvenient because without family members, it is difficult for patients to buy food in the cafeteria. Food often runs out early in the lunch cafeteria. When I bought spring rolls in the morning, the dipping sauce was sour. If the patient couldn't distinguish the taste, if he ate it, he would get sick. Will the hospital be responsible? - The hospital is a public place, I agree, but the hospital should advise patients and family members about the rules and maintain general quiet. It is impossible to listen to chanting at 3:30 a.m. and listen to political news at 4:30 a.m. , other times the person making the video call loudly, filming all over the room.
